{"title":"B. Nastia and a Good Array","contestId":"1521","problemIndex":"B","timeLimit":"2 seconds","memLimit":"256 megabytes","inputFormat":"standard input","outputFormat":"standard output","problemHtml":"<p><span class=\"tex-font-style-it\">Nastia has received an array of $$$n$$$ positive integers as a gift</span>.</p><p>She calls such an array $$$a$$$ good that for any $$$i$$$ ($$$2 \\le i \\le n$$$) takes place $$$gcd(a_{i - 1}, a_{i}) = 1$$$, where $$$gcd(u, v)$$$ denotes the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greatest_common_divisor\">greatest common divisor (GCD)</a> of integers $$$u$$$ and $$$v$$$.</p><p>You can perform the operation: select two <span class=\"tex-font-style-bf\">different</span> indices $$$i, j$$$ ($$$1 \\le i, j \\le n$$$, $$$i \\neq j$$$) and two integers $$$x, y$$$ ($$$1 \\le x, y \\le 2 \\cdot 10^9$$$). Then change the elements of array $$$a_i$$$ and $$$a_j$$$ to $$$x$$$ and $$$y$$$ respectively in a way that $$$\\min{(a_i, a_j)} = \\min{(x, y)}$$$.</p><p>The girl asks you to make the array good using <span class=\"tex-font-style-bf\">at most</span> $$$n$$$ operations.</p><p>It can be proven that this is always possible.</p>","inSpecsHtml":"<div class=\"section-title\">Input</div><p>The first line contains a single integer $$$t$$$ ($$$1 \\le t \\le 10\\,000$$$)&#xA0;&#x2014; the number of test cases.</p><p>The first line of each test case contains a single integer $$$n$$$ ($$$1 \\le n \\le 10^5$$$)&#xA0;&#x2014; the length of the array.</p><p>The second line of each test case contains $$$n$$$ integers $$$a_1, a_2, \\ldots, a_{n}$$$ ($$$1 \\le a_i \\le 10^9$$$)&#xA0;&#x2014; the array which Nastia has received as a gift.</p><p>It&apos;s guaranteed that the sum of $$$n$$$ in one test doesn&apos;t exceed $$$2 \\cdot 10^5$$$.</p>","outSpecsHtml":"<div class=\"section-title\">Output</div><p>For each of $$$t$$$ test cases print a single integer $$$k$$$ ($$$0 \\le k \\le n$$$)&#xA0;&#x2014; the number of operations.</p><p>In each of the next $$$k$$$ lines print $$$4$$$ integers $$$i$$$, $$$j$$$, $$$x$$$, $$$y$$$ ($$$1 \\le i \\neq j \\le n$$$, $$$1 \\le x, y \\le 2 \\cdot 10^9$$$) so that $$$\\min{(a_i, a_j)} = \\min{(x, y)}$$$&#xA0;&#x2014; in this manner you replace $$$a_i$$$ with $$$x$$$ and $$$a_j$$$ with $$$y$$$.</p>","noteHtml":"<div class=\"section-title\">Note</div><p>Consider the first test case.</p><p>Initially $$$a = [9, 6, 3, 11, 15]$$$.</p><p>In the first operation replace $$$a_1$$$ with $$$11$$$ and $$$a_5$$$ with $$$9$$$. It&apos;s valid, because $$$\\min{(a_1, a_5)} = \\min{(11, 9)} = 9$$$.</p><p>After this $$$a = [11, 6, 3, 11, 9]$$$.</p><p>In the second operation replace $$$a_2$$$ with $$$6$$$ and $$$a_5$$$ with $$$7$$$. It&apos;s valid, because $$$\\min{(a_2, a_5)} = \\min{(7, 6)} = 6$$$.</p><p>After this $$$a = [11, 7, 3, 11, 6]$$$&#xA0;&#x2014; a good array.</p><p>In the second test case, the initial array is already good.</p>","sampleTestcases":[{"id":1620399053457,"input":"2\n5\n9 6 3 11 15\n3\n7 5 13","output":"2\n1 5 11 9\n2 5 7 6\n0","result":{"id":1620399053457,"stdout":"2\r\n0 1 3 6\r\n1 2 5 3\r\n2\r\n0 1 3 5\r\n1 2 5 5\r\n","stderr":"","exitcode":0,"signal":null,"time":61,"timeout":false}}],"submitUrl":"https://codeforces.com/contest/1521/submit","language":"c++"}